we dont'no the length of the aruguments while defining a function .we use a varible argument function.
The elements will be collected using pointer(*)
(*)it  will accept the variable length argument from the function call
all elements will stroed in Tuple() as a output




def var(a):
    print(a)
    return
var(10)
#o/p=10


def var(a):     //function defination
    print(a)
    return
var(10,20      //function call
TypeError: var() takes 1 positional argument but 2 were given


===>so here we have to avoid to this error. we can use variable length argumens with help of(*)=============

def var(*a):         #varialbe length argument with(*)
    print(a)
    return
var(10)
#o/p= (10,)     # it will printed in tuple()



======we can use multiple date types also====

def var(*a):
    print(a)
    return
var(10,20.4,"bannysha")

#o/p=(10, 20.4, 'bannysha')


=====>elements in line by line=====

def var(*a):
    print("elements are:")
    for ele in a:
        print(ele)
    return
var(10,02.2,"bunny")


#output
elements are:
10
2.2
bunny




